{{italic title}} {{Infobox book <!-- |italic title = (see above) --> | name = ''Hortus Sanitatis'' | image = File:Hortus Sanitatis Frontispiece 1485.jpg | caption = Frontispiece of 1485 edition | author = | illustrator = | country = Germany | subject = | genre = | publisher = Jacob Meydenbach, Mainz | pub_date = 1491 | pages = | wikisource = }}
The '''''Hortus Sanitatis''''' (also written '''Ortus'''; [[Latin]] for '''''The Garden of Health'''''), the first [[natural history]] [[encyclopaedia]],<ref name=Attenborough>{{cite web |last1=Attenborough |first1=David |title=Ortus sanitatis |url=http://cudl.lib.cam.ac.uk/view/PR-INC-00003-A-00001-00008-00037 |publisher=Cambridge Digital Library |access-date=16 October 2014 |mode=cs2}}</ref> was published by Jacob Meydenbach in [[Mainz]], Germany in 1491.<ref name=Cambridge>{{cite web |title=Ortus sanitatis |url=http://cudl.lib.cam.ac.uk/view/PR-INC-00003-A-00001-00008-00037 |publisher=Cambridge Digital Library |access-date=16 October 2014 |mode=cs2}}</ref>
It describes species in the natural world along with their [[pharmacology|medicinal uses]] and modes of preparation.{{r|OpenLibrary}} It is in part an extended Latin translation of the ''German Herbarius'', the ''Gart der Gesundheit'' of Peter Schöffer, published in 1485 but, unlike that earlier work, also deals with animals, birds, fish and stones.{{sfnp|Arber|2010|p=28|ps=none}} The author does not restrict himself to dealing only with real creatures, but also includes accounts of [[mythical animals]] such as the [[dragon]], [[harpy]], [[Lernaean Hydra|hydra]], [[myrmecoleon]], [[Phoenix (mythology)|phoenix]], and [[zitiron]].{{sfnp|Arber|2010|pp=34–35|ps=none}}
==Context== The ''Hortus Sanitatis'' was the third important [[herbal]] to be printed in Mainz before 1500. The first two were by [[Peter Schoeffer]], his Latin ''Herbarius'' in 1484, followed by an updated and enlarged German version in 1485.{{sfnp|Raphael|1986|p=249|ps=none}}
==Publication history== [[File:Ortus 1497 frontispice.jpg|thumb|upright|Frontispiece of 1497 edition]] The first edition of ''Hortus Sanitatis'' was printed by Jacob Meydenbach in Mainz, Germany in 1485, with a second edition in 1491 and a third in 1497. A French edition by [[Antoine Vérard]] was printed in Paris in about 1500, under the title ''Ortus sanitatis translate de latin en francois''.{{sfnp|Arber|2010|p=35|ps=none}} The last complete copy of ''Hortus Sanitatis'' appeared in about 1539, printed by Phillipe le Noir and sold in Paris under the title of ''Le jardin de sante''.{{sfnp|Arber|2010|p=36|ps=none}}
An English version of extracts from the ''Hortus'', the ''Noble lyfe & natures of man, of bestes, serpentys, fowles & fisshes'', was produced in 1491 by Laurence Andrew (fl. 1510–1537). A facsimile edition of this was published in London in 1954 by B. Quaritch.<ref>{{cite web |title=An early English version of Hortus sanitatis : a recent bibliographical discovery by Noel Hudson |url=http://trove.nla.gov.au/work/21724021?selectedversion=NBD2964329 |publisher=NLA.gov.au |access-date=28 February 2016}}</ref>
==Contents== The book is divided up into sections as follows:<ref name=OpenLibrary>{{cite web |title=Ortus sanitatis |url=https://openlibrary.org/books/OL25129180M/Ortus_sanitatis |publisher=Open Library |accessdate=16 October 2014 |mode=cs2}}</ref> *''Tractatus De Herbis'' ("Treatise on Herbs") *''Tractatus De Animalibus'' ("Treatise on Animals") *''Tractatus De Avibus'' ("Treatise on Birds") *''Tractatus De Piscibus'' ("Treatise on Fish") *''Tractatus De Lapidibus'' ("Treatise on Stones") *''Tractatus De Urinis'' ("Treatise on Urine") *''Tabula super tractatu'' (an alphabetic index of medicinal uses for the species in each section) *''Tabula Generis'' (an alphabetic list of the contained species)
==Illustrations== The [[woodcut]] illustrations are stylised but often easily recognizable,{{r|Attenborough}} and many were re-used in other works.<ref name=RCP>{{cite web |title=Johannes de Cuba Ortus sanitatis |url=http://www.rcpe.ac.uk/sites/default/files/library_papers/crowe/cuba/cuba-index.php |publisher=Royal College of Physicians of Edinburgh |access-date=16 October 2014 |deadurl=yes |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141021001506/http://www.rcpe.ac.uk/sites/default/files/library_papers/crowe/cuba/cuba-index.php |archive-date=21 October 2014 |mode=cs2}}</ref> In addition to the representations of simples, pictures show their use by humans, and scenes in which figures are surrounded by the subjects in their natural environment, such as standing by a river with fish and mermaids.<ref name=Attenborough/> Unusually for the period, many of the woodcuts are coloured.<ref name="Aberdeen">{{cite web |last1=O'Sullivan |first1=Keith |title=Collections Highlight: Hortus Sanitatis (Garden of Health) |url=https://specialcollectionslearning.wordpress.com/2012/05/21/collection-highlight-hortus-sanitatis-garden-of-health/ |publisher=[[University of Aberdeen]] |access-date=28 February 2016 |mode=cs2}}</ref>
