[[File:TejonWest.jpg|thumb|Overlooking the eastern half of Tejon Ranch from the Tehachapi Crest of the Tehachapi Mountains, one of the Transverse Ranges.]]
[[File:Pyrite-Silver-Quartz-121767.jpg|thumb|Mineral scattered through the Canyons of San Emigdio, suggesting the presence of a mine nearby.]]
The '''Lost Padre mine''' is a [[List of lost mines|lost mine]] believed to be located in [[Southern California]], within the borders of the [[San Emigdio]] municipality in [[Ventura County, California|Northern Ventura County]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://rrchs.org/mininghistory.htm|title=The Ridge Route Communities Historical Society: Local Mining History |language=en-US|access-date=2017-04-07}}</ref>

==History==

According to historical accounts, the Lost Padre mine was created and operated by [[Missionary|Catholic missionaries]] and [[Native Americans in the United States|Native Americans]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Hudnall, Wang|first1=Ken, Connie|title=Spirits Of The Border: The History And Mystery Of Ft. Bliss Texas|pages=14|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=WmFAyV_fBvcC&lpg=PA14&ots=2A1UhwgMUR&dq=%22lost%20padre%20mine%22%20catholic%20missionaries&pg=PA14#v=onepage&q=%22lost%20padre%20mine%22%20catholic%20missionaries&f=false|accessdate=23 February 2017}}</ref> It is believed that the mine was in operation anywhere between the late [[17th century|17th]] and early [[19th century]]. However, earlier estimates are likely to be more accurate, due to indications that the [[Society of Jesus|Jesuit]] priests who funded the creation of the mine were dignitaries of [[Spain]] or Mexico.{{Citation needed|date=May 2017}}

The mine is reportedly home to large deposits of unrefined gold and silver, coming from veins of quartz pushed into the Southern California mountains by glaciers roughly 1.8 million years ago.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://glaciers.research.pdx.edu/glaciers-california|title=Glaciers of California {{!}} Glaciers of the American West|website=glaciers.research.pdx.edu|access-date=2016-09-27}}</ref> In addition, it is believed that the bodies of as many as 20 workers, mostly Native Americans, were buried in a cave-in.{{Citation needed|date=May 2017}} Upon its reported rediscovery in the 1800s, many of those seeking to return to the mine were killed in riding accidents on the way to the mine, either being thrown from their horses or falling down the cliffs of the [[San Emigdio Mountains|San Emigdio]] region.{{Citation needed|date=May 2017}}

==Twentieth century==

Throughout the [[20th century]], several groups have searched for the mine. The most notable and prominent example is the Edwards family. John Edwards has become the primary source of researchers, as his father and grandfather were both reportedly experts on the topic. Edwards' grandfather had reportedly rediscovered the mine shortly after [[World War I]], only disclosing its general vicinity within Doc Williams Canyon,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.topozone.com/california/kern-ca/valley/doc-williams-canyon/|title=Doc Williams Canyon Topo Map, Kern County CA (Eagle Rest Peak Area)|language=en-US|access-date=2016-09-27}}</ref>{{Citation needed|date=May 2017}} near [[Eagle Rest Peak]] in the mountains of [[Kern County, California|Kern County]].

==Recent==
The most recent attempt at rediscovery is by [[Jake Allard]], a local college student of [[Anthropology]] at [[Moorpark College]]. Allard has claimed to have made a total of 6 expeditions in the regions described by Edwards, following the San Emigdio Creek through the various canyons. During the most successful expedition, he was accompanied by three colleagues from Moorpark College and [[Carnegie Mellon University]]. The former include colleagues Austin Clarizio, Collin Chamberlain, and Roman Kaufman.

Allard believes the vicinity outlined by Edwards is the only feasible option, based on clues and context given in historical records, including nearby veins of silver and quartz, as well as gold dust discovered during the search. Artifacts discovered by Allard back up this claim. These include a late 18th or mid 19th-century mining tool, although its origins have not been confirmed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://scahome.org/counties/ventura/|title=Ventura {{!}} Society for California Archaeology|website=scahome.org|access-date=2016-09-27}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://miningartifacts.homestead.com/|title=Mining Artifacts|website=miningartifacts.homestead.com|access-date=2016-09-27}}</ref>

Hundreds of hours of charting and mapping have resulted in the location of the mine being narrowed down to roughly 8 square miles. As of May 2017, Jake Allard has discovered one physical mine in the vicinity of Eagle Rest Peak.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://twitter.com/JakeAllard/status/862558390274347008|title=Jake Allard on Twitter|work=Twitter|access-date=2017-05-27|language=en}}</ref> Despite not being a part of the Lost Padre mine, it shows promise that an [[Vein (geology)|exposed vein of ore]] may be within a reasonable distance. Allard argues that an open pit mining operation would be the most probable structure of the mine, given the location and time it was operated.{{Citation needed|date=May 2017}}

==Red Rock Canyon Mine==
Some theories suggest the Red Rock Canyon mine, located near [[Castaic, California|Castaic]], is actually an offshoot vein of the Lost Padre mine. However, there are several issues with this claim. The Red Rock mine, for example, was discovered in the 19th century and worked until 1935, over one hundred years after the Lost Padre mine was said to be in operation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.lagoldmines.com/index.php?page=532670.txt|title=Gold Mines of Los Angeles County|website=www.lagoldmines.com|access-date=2016-09-27}}</ref> Some, including Jake Allard, dispute this claim, having mapped a path to the Red Rock mine in 2016 in an attempt to collect evidence of late Mexican or early American creation of the Red Rock Canyon mine, as opposed to by Jesuit missionaries.{{Citation needed|date=May 2017}}

==In popular culture==
A film has been produced, entitled ''Lost Padre Mine'', directed by David Noble. The film centers on the legend of the Lost Padre mine, following the character of Wayne Braddock, a treasure hunter who arrives in El Paso in search of missing gold.<ref>{{Citation|title=Lost Padre Mine (2017)|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt4730632/|accessdate=2017-05-27}}</ref>

